## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical firewall configuration skills on RHEL 9, requiring precise rule creation, persistence, and verification—essential for enterprise security administration.

## Key Concepts
- nftables ruleset syntax and packet flow
- Rule persistence via /etc/nftables.conf
- Service management with systemctl
- Connectivity testing from allowed vs. disallowed sources
- Verification using nft list ruleset

## Code Example
```bash
#!/usr/sbin/nft -f
flush ruleset
table inet filter {
  chain input {
    type filter hook input priority 0; policy drop;
    iifname "lo" accept
    ip saddr 192.168.1.0/24 tcp dport 22 accept
  }
  chain forward {
    type filter hook forward priority 0; policy drop;
  }
  chain output {
    type filter hook output priority 0; policy accept;
  }
}
```

## Implementation Steps
```bash
# Install nftables
dnf install -y nftables

# Create ruleset
cat > /etc/nftables.conf << 'EOF'
#!/usr/sbin/nft -f
flush ruleset
table inet filter {
  chain input {
    type filter hook input priority 0; policy drop;
    iifname "lo" accept
    ip saddr 192.168.1.0/24 tcp dport 22 accept
  }
  chain forward {
    type filter hook forward priority 0; policy drop;
  }
  chain output {
    type filter hook output priority 0; policy accept;
  }
}
EOF

# Enable and start services
systemctl enable nftables
systemctl start nftables
systemctl status nftables

# Verify rules
nft list ruleset

# Test connectivity (from allowed host)
ssh user@server-ip

# Test connectivity (from disallowed host)
ssh user@server-ip  # Should timeout/refuse
```
